Findings, most severe first:

1. BLOCKING — Per-session inbound rate limiter (backend/app/middleware/
   ratelimit.py) is completely and trivially bypassable by never
   persisting/returning the session cookie; the §10.5-mandated per-IP
   backstop is dead code in the real wiring, not a functioning defense.
   Verified empirically: a script issuing `POST /search` from a fresh,
   cookie-less client each time (functionally equivalent to any HTTP
   client that doesn't use a cookie jar, or that discards Set-Cookie) hit
   30/30 requests with 200s against a route capped at 10/minute — the
   limiter never engaged once. Cause: `session_or_ip_key()` reads
   `request.state.session.session_id`, and `SessionIdentityMiddleware`
   (wired ahead of the rate limiter, per main.py's own documented order)
   unconditionally mints a brand-new `Session` row + session_id whenever
   no valid cookie is presented — so a cookie-churning caller gets a
   fresh rate-limit bucket key on every request, and the per-IP fallback
   (`get_remote_address`) is only reached if `request.state.session` is
   entirely unset, which never happens in the live stack (session
   middleware always runs first and always resolves *a* session). This
   directly defeats SPEC.md §10.5's explicit purpose for the limiter
   ("Shared-budget exhaustion" and "Using LitList as a free,
   unauthenticated PubMed/Zotero-writing proxy") — an attacker script
   hitting `/search`, `/zotero/push`, `/export.csv`, or
   `/papers/{pmid}/abstract` directly, bypassing the UI, faces
   effectively zero throttling. It also causes unbounded `Session` table
   growth (a new DB row per abusive request, no cap), a secondary
   DB-bloat/DoS angle. tester's TASK 3D VERIFY item 3 ("IP fallback key
   verified directly") tested only the unit function `session_or_ip_key()`
   in isolation with a synthetic request that never had a resolved
   session — not the actual attack surface (a live request through the
   full stack that never returns a cookie) — so this gap survived both
   the specialist's own tests and tester's two verification passes.
   Reported back for a real per-IP (or per-IP+route) ceiling that applies
   independently of session churn, e.g. always also charging an IP-keyed
   budget regardless of whether a session was freshly minted this
   request, or capping how many new `Session` rows a single IP may create
   per minute.

2. SIGNIFICANT — A generator-based streaming response that raises after
   its headers have already been flushed (e.g. `GET /export.csv`'s row
   iterator hitting a DB error partway through the Saved List) is not
   converted to CONTRACTS.md §2's safe error shape, contradicting
   errors.py's own docstring claim that this covers "any unhandled
   exception... regardless of exception type." Verified empirically with
   a minimal repro (a `StreamingResponse` generator that yields two rows
   then raises `RuntimeError`, run through the real
   `install_exception_handlers`): the client receives HTTP 200 with a
   truncated/empty body, not a 500 with the pinned JSON error body — once
   `http.response.start` has been sent with a 200 status, that status
   cannot be retroactively changed, so the exception handler's JSON
   response can never actually reach the client for this failure mode.
   No secret currently leaks through this specific path (export.csv's
   fields are already-sanitized local DB data, not raw exception text),
   so this is not a live credential-leak repeat of the Tier 1 pattern,
   but it is a real, verified gap in the "every response gets the safe
   shape" guarantee, and it produces a user-visible failure that's
   indistinguishable from "the Saved List happens to be empty" (a
   silently truncated/incomplete CSV posing as a successful export)
   rather than a detectable error. Neither tester's VERIFY nor RE-VERIFY
   entries exercised a streaming route under a mid-generator failure —
   both rounds tested only non-streaming routes and mid-*middleware*
   exceptions. Reported back so export.csv's generator can either wrap
   its DB iteration in a way that emits a detectable
   truncation/sentinel, or the row query can run to completion before
   any bytes are streamed (trading the streaming memory benefit for
   correctness) if partial-failure detection matters for this data.

3. Non-finding (verified, does not hold up) — Pydantic/FastAPI
   response-model serialization failures. Tested directly: a route
   returning data that fails its declared `response_model` type raises
   `fastapi.exceptions.ResponseValidationError` *before* any bytes are
   sent (`serialize_response` runs ahead of `response(scope, receive,
   send)`), so it is caught by the same global `Exception` handler and
   correctly returns the safe 500 body. This concern from the review
   brief does not reproduce as a gap.

4. Non-finding (verified) — CORS/CSRF real-world bypass attempts.
   `_allowed_origins()`/`CSRFGuardMiddleware` use exact string equality
   (`origin not in _allowed_origins()`), which correctly rejects both a
   query-string trick (`https://evil.com?real-origin=https://
   localhost:5173`) and a subdomain trick (`https://localhost.5173.evil.
   com`) — neither string-equals a configured origin. The "no Origin
   header → allowed" default is a deliberate, documented fail-open
   choice; verified it doesn't reopen classic CSRF because every
   body-bearing state-changing endpoint still requires
   `Content-Type: application/json`, which an HTML `<form>` (the classic
   CSRF delivery mechanism) cannot produce regardless of Origin — so the
   two checks are complementary, not one masking a gap in the other.
   Security headers are confirmed applied to every response including
   403/429/500 paths (`SecurityHeadersMiddleware` is the outermost layer
   in main.py's wiring, verified against the actual `add_middleware` call
   order). Route-level exception handling in 3A/3B/3C (`except ApiError`,
   `except PubMedParseError`, etc.) is all internal try/except that
   returns directly — none of it relies on FastAPI's
   `@app.exception_handler` MRO resolution, so there is no
   shadowing/interference risk with Task 3D's global handlers. No finding
   in any of these four areas.

