Verified and found NOT to be problems (actively tried to break each):
- **§4.5-vs-§13.6 priority race**: `getErrorCopy()` checks `isOffline`
  before `error.code === "service_unavailable"` unconditionally
  (errorCopy.ts:42-53), and `isOffline` is read reactively from
  `networkStore` by the calling component at render time, not captured
  at request-send time — so even a stale/in-flight request that resolves
  with a `service_unavailable` body *after* the browser has already gone
  offline still renders "You're offline" once the offline-triggered
  re-render happens, because the offline check runs on the *current*
  store value, not a frozen one. §11.5 also confirms the service worker
  never caches PubMed/API responses (only the static app shell), so the
  "stale cached error response" variant of this scenario is architecturally
  not possible as constructed. `errorCopy.test.ts`'s second test directly
  asserts the priority claim with a real `service_unavailable` error
  object present alongside `isOffline: true`. No collapse found.
- **Retry-queue lost-update under network flapping**: `retryAll()` only
  removes an item after `await item.run()` resolves without throwing
  (retryQueueStore.ts:63-71); a network drop mid-retry causes the
  underlying fetch to reject, which is caught and leaves the item
  queued — no scenario found where an item is dropped without its retry
  actually completing. A second `online` event firing mid-drain is a
  no-op via the `isRetrying` guard (retryQueueStore.ts:59), so no
  overlapping drain/double-fire race exists either.
- **Duplicate-enqueue dedup**: `enqueue()` filters out any existing item
  with the same `id` before appending (retryQueueStore.ts:47-52), so a
  caller using a stable id (e.g. keyed by pmid/action) gets automatic
  dedup rather than duplicate retries. (Real double-press behavior
  ultimately depends on 4A/4B choosing stable ids when they wire real
  actions in — outside 4C's scope to verify further since nothing calls
  `enqueue` from a real screen yet, confirmed via grep.)
- **CookieConsentNotice persistence**: does NOT persist across reload
  (plain in-memory Zustand store, no `persist` middleware) — but this
  matches SPEC.md §10.2/§11.7's own wording exactly ("dismissed *this
  session*", "local UI state... not persisted") word for word, and
  uiStore.ts's own comment cites this correctly. Verified this is the
  intended design, not an oversight.
- **ErrorState XSS surface**: `{title}`/`{message}` are rendered as
  plain JSX text-node children (ErrorState.tsx:49-50), never via
  `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` — React's default text-node escaping applies,
  consistent with the project's established pattern. No injection
  surface found even under a hypothetical adversarial `error.message`.

Nothing else survived scrutiny beyond the above three items (one
significant, one confirmed-still-open minor, one informational).

