FINDING 1 — BLOCKING: mid-narration decisions never call
`speechSynthesis.cancel()`, directly violating SPEC.md §6.6's explicit
hard requirement ("Swiping must call `speechSynthesis.cancel()`
immediately ... This must happen synchronously with the swipe handler
so there is no audible overlap between papers"). Verified by reading
`App.tsx`'s `decide()` closure end to end and grepping the whole
`frontend/src` tree for `engine.cancel`/`.cancel(`: the only call sites
of `usePlaybackEngine`'s `cancel()` are inside the hook's own
implementation (pause/unmount-cleanup) — `App.tsx` never calls it.
`decide()` calls `playback.resetForNewPaper()` (a Zustand store method)
which only flips `isPlaying`/`highlightedSegmentIndex` to
false/null — it does not touch the actual `SpeechSynthesisUtterance`
in flight inside `usePlaybackEngine`, which is a *separate* module
holding its own `statusRef`/`generationRef`/`currentUtteranceRef`
(confirmed by reading `usePlaybackEngine.ts` and `state/
playbackStore.ts` together). Concrete failure sequence: user swipes/taps
a decision while the current paper's abstract is still being narrated.
`decide()` fires the PATCH + optimistic queue update; `currentItem`
advances to the next paper next render, so the `items` `useMemo` swaps
to the new paper's `[title, metadata, ...segments]` and `itemsRef.
current` is overwritten via the hook's own `useEffect([items])` —
*while the old paper's browser-native utterance is still speaking,
uninterrupted*. When that stale utterance's real `onend` eventually
fires, the `generation !== generationRef.current` guard does **not**
catch it (generation is only bumped by `play()`/`pause()`/`cancel()`,
none of which `decide()` calls), so `scheduleGap(index + 1, generation)`
runs and reads `itemsRef.current` — now the *new* paper's item list —
at an index carried over from the *old* paper. This produces either (a)
audible overlap/wrong-paper narration (SPEC's own named failure mode),
(b) playback jumping into the middle of the new paper's segments
(desyncing the sentence highlight from what's actually spoken, contra
§6.5), or (c) an out-of-bounds index immediately calling `finish()` for
the new paper the user hasn't heard at all, firing an unwanted
auto-decide (`onFinished` -> `decide(newPmid, defaultSwipeBehavior,
"auto")`) before the user ever interacted with that card. Also a
secondary, related desync: `resetForNewPaper()`'s direct write to
`playback.isPlaying` violates this codebase's own documented invariant
(App.tsx's and playbackStore.ts's own comments: "the engine stays the
one source of truth for *whether* narration is playing; the store is a
read-only reflection ... never an independently toggled duplicate") —
here the store is toggled directly, out of band from the engine's real
`status`, so the play/pause button and highlight can show "stopped"
while the engine is still actually speaking. Confirmed zero test
coverage of this path anywhere (grepped all `*.test.ts*` for `cancel(`
outside `usePlaybackEngine.test.ts` itself — no hit in `App.test.tsx`
or any StackScreen-level test), so this was never exercised, not just
untested-but-passing. This is the specific "swipe cancellation" case
SPEC.md calls a hard requirement, not a style nicety, and it sits
squarely inside this task's own core-loop scope (§11.4's decision
function + §11.3's playback module handoff) — not an adjacent task's
responsibility. Neither the specialist's COMPLETE entry, its
post-verification PIVOT, nor either of tester's two VERIFY passes
mention checking for a `cancel()` call at the decision site.

