delay fires at ~20-30/s; two fast manual keypresses, or two fast taps of
the Interested/Skip buttons, reach the same window) both read the same
stale `currentItem` closure and both call `decide(pmid, decision,
"swipe")` for the *same* pmid. Traced `useUpdateDecision`'s `onMutate`
(`decisions.ts`) for the actual consequence: since `onMutate` is async
and its first statement is `await queryClient.cancelQueries(...)`, two
back-to-back synchronous `mutate()` calls both start executing before
either resolves, so the *second* call's `previousQueue` snapshot is
taken *after* the first call's optimistic write has already landed
(each `onMutate` resumes in turn) — meaning if the *first* PATCH later
fails, its `onError` rollback restores the pre-decision `previousQueue`
snapshot and **overwrites the second (successful) call's optimistic
decision**, transiently showing the item as `pending` again in the UI
even though the server has already recorded the second call's decision
as final; this self-heals once `onSettled`'s `invalidateQueries` runs,
but produces a real, visible incorrect intermediate state. More
importantly, verified against the actual backend
(`backend/app/routes/decisions.py`'s `update_decision`): the PATCH
handler unconditionally overwrites `decision_row.decision` with
whatever the current request's body says, with no optimistic-locking or
"already decided" check — so if the two racing requests are received
out of order (plausible under real network conditions, not just
localhost), the *server's* final recorded decision for that pmid may
not match the *user's actual last keypress*, silently. This is exactly
the class of race the task's own review brief asked to be checked for.

